ore of the Wyandot people and told in a language that has been dormant for decades, act as a time capsule for traditional tales, Indigenous history, humour, and Elder knowledge. Steckley's new translation not only aids Wyandot peoples of Oklahoma, Kansas, and Michigan in reclaiming their language but also gives researchers worldwide a rich, up-to-date reference for linguistic study. A significant literary record of a people and a language, Forty Narratives in the Wyandot Language is a major contribution to the preservation and revitalization of an Indigenous language in North America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWyandot languagevTexts. 0aWyandot languagexStudy and teaching. 0aWyandot languagexTranslating into English. 0aWyandot language. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020z978311127473740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228005155?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228005155423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228005155/original  a978-3-11-127253-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-127473-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles